WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.280
 Have you ever wondered what is a pointer?

00:00:02.280 --> 00:00:05.759
 A pointer is a variable that stores the address of another variable,

00:00:05.759 --> 00:00:09.000
 instead of storing a normal value like an integer or a character.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:11.040
 Think of a pointer as a signpost.

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:12.560
 It doesn't hold the data itself.

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:15.080
 It just tells you where that data lives in memory.

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:17.280
 For example, when you break 10,

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:20.199
 P, on the other hand, holds the address of X.

00:00:20.199 --> 00:00:23.559
 Separate two closely related ideas, declaration and definition.

00:00:23.559 --> 00:00:26.280
 When we declare a pointer the type of data it will point to.

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:29.679
 When we define it, we actually create that pointer variable in memory.

00:00:29.839 --> 00:00:31.960
 For instance, int asterisptr.

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:34.799
 Sline both declares and defines a pointer called PTR

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:36.000
 that can point to an integer.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:37.560
 Right now it doesn't point anywhere meaningful.

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:40.560
 It contains an undefined or garbage address.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:43.399
 That's why it's good practice to initialize pointers before using them.

00:00:43.399 --> 00:00:45.320
 Now let's talk about initialization.

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:49.159
 A pointer is a special type of variable that stores the memory address of another variable

00:00:49.159 --> 00:00:50.840
 instead of holding a direct value.

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:55.600
 To make a pointer useful, it must be initialized by assigning it the address of an existing variable.

00:00:55.600 --> 00:00:58.560
 The address of operator, written as an ampersand,

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:00.359
 is used to obtain the address of a variable.

00:01:00.359 --> 00:01:02.800
 The pointer is pointing to a valid memory location.

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:07.600
 You can use the dereference operator to access or modify the data stored there.

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:10.799
 D-referencing means go to the address that this pointer holds

00:01:10.799 --> 00:01:14.200
 and fetch or change the value that lives at that location.

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:18.800
 This makes pointers very powerful because you can indirectly read or change the contents of variables

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:20.680
 without referring to them by name.

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:24.040
 For example, if an integer variable holds the value 42

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:28.520
 and a dereferencing that pointer gives you access to the number 42 itself.

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:30.359
 If you change the value through the pointer,

00:01:30.359 --> 00:01:35.040
 the original variables value also changes because they both refer to the same place in memory.

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:38.079
 If you were to display the value stored in a pointer,

00:01:38.079 --> 00:01:41.320
 usually shown as a long hexadecimal number.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:45.560
 This number represents the specificer's memory where the variable is located.

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:48.439
 If you display the value obtained by dereferencing the pointer,

00:01:48.439 --> 00:01:51.680
 you'll see the actual data stored at that address.

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:54.439
 Pointers are not just about accessing variables indirectly.

00:01:54.439 --> 00:01:57.560
 They are also essential for many advanced programming techniques.

00:01:57.560 --> 00:02:01.640
 They allow functions to modify variables outside their local scope.

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:05.400
 Make it possible to create dynamic data structures like linked lists and trees

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:08.920
 and enable efficient handling of large amounts of data by passing addresses

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:11.000
 instead of copying entire values.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.840
 However, because pointers give direct access to memory, they must be used carefully.

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:17.800
 Using an uninitialized pointer or one that points to invalid memory

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:21.840
 can cause serious errors such as crashes or unpredictable behavior.

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:24.159
 That's why initializing pointers properly

00:02:24.159 --> 00:02:27.319
 by assigning them valid addresses is so important.

00:02:27.319 --> 00:02:32.280
 A pointer acts as a bridge between a variable's name and its actual memory location.

00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:35.319
 So finally, declaring a pointer specifies its type,

00:02:35.319 --> 00:02:37.319
 defining it allocates space for it,

00:02:37.319 --> 00:02:41.680
 and initializing it as the address of a valid variable so it points to real memory.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:45.439
 The referencing is how we access and even modify data through a pointer.

00:02:45.439 --> 00:02:48.079
 Let's take this code in AI8.

00:02:48.079 --> 00:02:50.799
 After these three lines, the variable A now contains 8.

00:02:50.799 --> 00:02:52.120
 We didn't change A directly.

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:54.400
 We changed it indirectly through the pointer P.

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:57.280
 So op-e means the value stored at the address contained in P.

00:02:57.280 --> 00:03:02.240
 It's a level of interaction that allows C to manipulate to my pointers are so powerful.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:05.560
 Beginners often run into three classic pointer errors.

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:08.159
 First, using an uninitialized pointer.

00:03:08.159 --> 00:03:10.800
 If you declare a pointer but never assign it a valid address,

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:13.200
 it points to a random memory location.

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:17.680
 Writing through such a pointer causes unpredictable results or crashes.

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:19.759
 Second, forgetting to use null.

00:03:19.759 --> 00:03:24.240
 Always initialize unused pointers with null, which means points to nothing.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.680
 That makes it safe to check if P.

00:03:26.680 --> 00:03:29.280
 Third, mixing types.

00:03:29.280 --> 00:03:33.680
 For example, a char should point to characters and an int should point to integers.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:38.080
 If the types don't match, the program may misinterpret the data.

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:40.680
 Another common issue with pointers is dangling pointers.

00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:45.680
 This happens when a pointer still refers to a memory location that's been freed or is no longer valid.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:50.640
 For example, if you free a block of memory using free PTR but forget to set PTR null,

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:54.239
 then trying to access PTR can cause crashes or data corruption.

00:03:54.239 --> 00:03:58.319
 The rule of thumb is, after freeing memory, always set the pointer to null.

00:03:58.319 --> 00:04:00.479
 Another point to remember is pointer arithmetic.

00:04:00.479 --> 00:04:05.119
 When you add or subtract integers from a pointer, it moves by the size of the data type it points to.

00:04:05.119 --> 00:04:06.799
 Not by bytes directly.

00:04:06.799 --> 00:04:12.399
 For example, if P is an int, then P plus 1 moves ahead by 4 bytes, assuming int is 4 bytes.

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:14.560
 Pointer arithmetic is powerful when working with arrays,

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:18.479
 but if done incorrectly, it can easily lead to accessing out of bounds memory.

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:24.400
 Finally, pointers can also be used with functions to return multiple values or modify arguments directly.

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:29.600
 This is especially useful in C since functions normally return only one value.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:34.720
 By passing the address of variables, we allow the function to update the caller's data directly.

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:37.920
 Another reason pointers are essential in low-level programming.

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:39.280
 Let's recap.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:42.080
 A pointer is a variable that stores an address.

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:46.400
 You declare it using an asterisk, initialize it using the address operator,

00:04:46.399 --> 00:04:49.359
 and access or modify data with the dereference operator.

00:04:49.359 --> 00:04:53.199
 Declaration defines the type, initialization assigns an address,

00:04:53.199 --> 00:04:56.639
 and dereferencing lets you read or write the value indirectly.

00:04:56.639 --> 00:05:02.479
 And short int, pp declares a pointer point to p and x, initializes it, p here 20,

00:05:02.479 --> 00:05:03.679
 changes x through p.

00:05:04.319 --> 00:05:09.759
 Pointers are the keys that unlock arrays, strings, and dynamic memory allocation in C.

00:05:09.759 --> 00:05:12.719
 Understanding them well will make every other concept easier.

00:05:13.359 --> 00:05:14.479
 Thanks for watching.

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:16.480
 Keep coding. Keep exploring. Happy learning!

